# Codex Build Prompt: TK-MIA Software Planning Package

You are helping build **TK-MIA: ThyssenKrupp Manufacturing Intelligence Agent**.

Create a complete software development plan for a local-first manufacturing intelligence platform that helps engineering and shop-floor personnel with NC program review, setup sheets, tooling inventory, fixture inventory, photo documentation, and job-linked manufacturing knowledge.

## Core Mission

Build an extensible AI employee for the engineering department that behaves like a:

* Senior Manufacturing Engineer
* CNC Programmer
* CAM Developer
* Tooling Coordinator
* Manufacturing Documentation Specialist

The software must be:

* Modular
* Extensible
* Local-first
* Human-in-the-loop
* Auditable
* Version controlled
* Safe for production environments
* Useful to both engineering and shop-floor machinists

## Most Important MVP

Start with an **NC Program Parser + Setup Sheet Generator + Tooling/Fixture Photo Library**.

The system should ingest NC files such as:

* `.nc`
* `.tap`
* `.eia`
* `.txt`

It should extract:

* Tool numbers
* Tool comments
* Work offsets such as G54, G55, G56
* Operation sequence
* Feeds
* Speeds
* Drill cycles
* Tap cycles
* Probing cycles
* Rotary moves
* Estimated cycle time
* Safety/risk flags
* Setup notes

Then generate:

* Setup sheet draft
* Tool list
* Operator notes
* Inspection notes
* JSON report
* Excel report
* PDF setup sheet

## Setup Photo Reference System

The setup sheet should support photo references instead of requiring CAD-rendered setup graphics.

Example:

* Photo A — Raw stock
* Photo B — Fixture assembly
* Photo C — Vise stop location
* Photo D — G54 location
* Photo E — Tool layout
* Photo F — Clamp locations
* Photo G — Inspection points
* Photo H — Overall setup

The setup sheet may say:

“Reference Photo H for fixture visual.”

The photo library should store actual shop-floor photos and connect them to:

* Job number
* NC program
* Machine
* Fixture
* Tooling
* Work offset
* Setup sheet
* Operator notes

## Tooling Numbering System

Reserve **L-Series exclusively for lathe tooling** using the uploaded 5-digit lathe framework.

Lathe categories:

* L10000-L19999 — Rough Turning
* L20000-L29999 — Finish Turning
* L30000-L39999 — Boring Bars
* L40000-L49999 — Grooving & Parting
* L50000-L59999 — Threading
* L60000-L69999 — Drills
* L70000-L79999 — Reamers
* L80000-L89999 — Taps
* L90000-L99999 — Live Tooling / Milling / Specialty Attachments

Create a separate expanded **M-Series** for milling tools.

Suggested milling categories:

* M10000-M19999 — Roughing End Mills
* M20000-M29999 — Finishing End Mills
* M30000-M39999 — Ball End Mills / 3D Profiling
* M40000-M49999 — Chamfer / Deburr / Spotting
* M50000-M59999 — Drilling Tools
* M60000-M69999 — Tapping & Threading
* M70000-M79999 — Reaming / Boring / Hole Finishing
* M80000-M89999 — Face Milling / Shell Milling
* M90000-M99999 — Specialty Milling Tools

Expanded milling subcategories should include:

* Variable flute roughers
* Serrated roughers
* High-efficiency milling tools
* Aluminum roughers
* Steel roughers
* Stainless roughers
* Indexable roughers
* Long-reach roughers
* Variable flute finishers
* Corner-radius finishers
* Stub ball mills
* Long-reach ball mills
* Tapered ball mills
* Lollipop cutters
* Barrel cutters
* Circle-segment cutters
* Chamfer mills
* Spot drills
* Engravers
* Deburr tools
* Countersinks
* Back-chamfer tools
* Twist drills
* Carbide drills
* Indexable drills
* Coolant-through drills
* Step drills
* Gun drills
* Counterbores
* Standard taps
* Metric taps
* Pipe taps
* Form taps
* Thread mills
* Reamers
* Boring heads
* Fine boring heads
* Face mills
* Shell mills
* High-feed mills
* Shoulder mills
* Copy mills
* Fly cutters
* Dovetail cutters
* T-slot cutters
* Woodruff cutters
* Keyseat cutters
* Slitting saws
* Form tools
* Diamond tools
* Composite tools
* Custom tools

Also create separate prefixes:

* H-Series — Holders
* F-Series — Fixtures
* V-Series — Vises, jaws, stops, clamps
* P-Series — Probes and inspection tools
* R-Series — Router tools

## Photo-Based Inventory Vision

The software should allow users to take photos of:

* Tool drawers
* Toolboxes
* Tool carts
* Holders
* Fixture carts
* Vises
* Soft jaws
* Stops
* Inspection setups
* Full machine setups

Then the system should create or update inventory records from those photos.

Each inventory record should include:

* Internal ID
* Description
* Tool family
* Vendor
* Manufacturer part number
* Serial number if applicable
* Holder ID
* Machine compatibility
* Location
* Cabinet
* Drawer
* Quantity on hand
* Quantity in machines
* Minimum reorder quantity
* Programs used on
* Jobs used on
* Setup photos
* Notes
* Revision history

Actual shop-floor photos are preferred. Manufacturer catalog images may be stored as secondary references. AI-generated tool images should only be used as placeholders, never as proof of real inventory.

## Manufacturing Knowledge Graph

Design the system so TK-MIA can answer questions like:

* What tools do I need to run this job?
* Where is the fixture stored?
* Which drawer has the tap?
* What holder was used last time?
* What photo shows the G54 location?
* Which programs use this fixture?
* Which tools are duplicated across the shop?
* Which tools should be standardized?
* What should be reordered?
* What setup should the machinist use for this program?

## Safety Requirements

The system must never overwrite production files.

Required behavior:

* Original files stay untouched
* AI-created files receive revision names
* Suggested changes require engineer approval
* Every recommendation must be auditable
* Read-only mode must be available
* Program posting requires approval
* Tooling and fixture records keep revision history

Example revision names:

* `part123_v01`
* `part123_v02`
* `part123_AI_REVIEW`
* `part123_ENGINEER_APPROVED`

## Suggested Architecture

Backend:

* Python
* FastAPI
* Postgres
* SQLAlchemy
* Pydantic
* Local file storage
* ChromaDB or FAISS for searchable knowledge
* OpenAI API for AI review and documentation assistance

Frontend:

* React
* Electron desktop app
* Shop-floor-friendly UI
* Large buttons
* Simple search
* Photo upload workflow
* Barcode / QR code support later

Plugin framework:

* `plugin_nc_parser`
* `plugin_haas`
* `plugin_router`
* `plugin_lathe`
* `plugin_mastercam`
* `plugin_alphacam`
* `plugin_inventory`
* `plugin_setupsheet`
* `plugin_photo_library`

## Adoption Plan for Shop Floor

The software must be designed so machinists see direct benefit from the extra documentation work.

Do not make the shop floor feel like they are doing paperwork for engineering. The system should give them something useful back immediately.

Benefits to highlight:

* Less time searching for fixtures
* Less time searching for tools
* Fewer unclear setups
* Easier repeat jobs
* Faster first-piece setup
* Better photos for G54 and fixture locations
* Less tribal knowledge trapped in one person’s head
* Easier training for newer machinists
* Better night-shift and weekend support
* Fewer interruptions asking “where is this tool?”
* Reduced setup mistakes
* Easier reordering of common tools

Recommended rollout:

1. Start with one machine or one department.
2. Pick repeat jobs with known setup pain.
3. Generate setup sheets from existing NC files.
4. Add photo references A-H.
5. Label only the most-used tools and fixtures first.
6. Show machinists how the system saves setup/search time.
7. Collect feedback from actual users.
8. Improve templates before expanding.
9. Roll out department by department.

